──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  A 403 / 406 / 410 / 429 / timeout is usually a bot-block, a
  geo-block, or a JavaScript-rendered page — not a dead link.
  Go back to Brain/Reference/Platforms.md and work EVERY solution
  available for the failing platform, in order, before changing
  the guide:
    1. Is the host already marked ⚡/❌ in Platforms.md? If so the
       link is presumed valid — add it to BOT_BLOCKED_HOSTS here
       (verify_urls.py) so it warns instead of fails.
    2. site: search  — `site:{domain} {city} {subject}` (WebSearch);
       inspect the snippet for the exact product/article URL.
    3. Chrome MCP    — navigate to the URL, then get_page_text.
    4. Chrome MCP JS — when the page never reaches document_idle
       (heavy SPA: Viator, GetYourGuide, TripAdvisor), use
       javascript_tool to read the page's JSON-LD aggregateRating /
       <h1> directly instead of waiting for get_page_text.
    5. Only after every cascade step fails for a genuinely dead
       link: replace it with a different verified link, or remove
       the row and park the reason in ❓ Open Questions.
  Removing a link without working the cascade above is a violation.
